const DOP_QUESTIONS = [{"cat": "high-availability", "q": "A stateful application running on EC2 needs to complete in-flight transactions before Auto Scaling terminates an instance. Which feature enables this?", "options": ["A. EC2 Instance Protection", "B. Auto Scaling Lifecycle Hooks during instance termination", "C. Auto Scaling Standby state", "D. ELB connection draining"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Lifecycle Hooks pause instance termination and send a notification. The application can complete in-flight work and send a CompleteLifecycleAction signal. ELB connection draining handles existing connections separately."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "A company uses AWS OpsWorks and needs to update application code across all instances.", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "Which EC2 Auto Scaling feature allows you to protect specific instances from being terminated during scale-in?", "options": ["A. Auto Scaling warm pools", "B. Instance Scale-In Protection", "C. Auto Scaling Lifecycle Hooks", "D. EC2 Termination Protection"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Scale-In Protection can be set at the Auto Scaling group level (protecting all instances) or on individual instances. Protected instances are skipped during scale-in events, useful for instances processing long-running jobs."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "A company is deploying an application update to 500 EC2 instances. They want to minimize downtime while ensuring quick rollback capability. Which deployment strategy is most suitable?", "options": ["A. All-at-once deployment to all instances", "B. Blue/green deployment with two complete environments", "C. Rolling deployment updating instances in batches", "D. One-at-a-time sequential deployment"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Blue/green deployment maintains two identical production environments, allowing old instances to be terminated after validation, providing safe rollback capability."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "Your CDK Stack references resources in another Stack in a different AWS account.", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "A company wants to run integration tests against a real AWS environment in CodePipeline without hardcoding AWS credentials. What is the best practice?", "options": ["A. Store AWS credentials in CodeBuild environment variables", "B. Assign an IAM role to the CodeBuild project with least-privilege permissions for test resources", "C. Use the root account credentials stored in Secrets Manager", "D. Create a dedicated IAM user with admin access for testing"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CodeBuild projects assume IAM service roles for AWS API access. The role grants only the permissions needed for tests, eliminating the need for stored credentials and following least privilege principles."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "You need to deploy the same CloudFormation stack to 50 AWS accounts across 5 regions simultaneously. Which feature enables this?", "options": ["A. Run CloudFormation 250 times manually", "B. AWS CloudFormation StackSets with AWS Organizations integration", "C. Use CodePipeline with 50 parallel stages", "D. AWS Control Tower account factory"], "answer": 1, "explain": "StackSets can deploy stacks to multiple accounts and regions in a single operation. With AWS Organizations integration, you can target OUs and automatically include new accounts."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "A company needs to retain CloudWatch Logs for 7 years for compliance. What is the most cost-effective approach?", "options": ["A. Set CloudWatch Logs retention to 7 years in the log group settings", "B. Export logs to S3 with appropriate lifecycle policies using subscription filters or export tasks", "C. Store logs in RDS for long-term retention", "D. Use AWS Backup to backup CloudWatch Logs"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CloudWatch Logs maximum retention is 10 years but at higher cost. Exporting logs to S3 is more cost-effective. S3 lifecycle rules can transition to Glacier for very long-term cheap storage."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "Your CDK application needs to reference outputs from manually created AWS resources.", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "Which AWS service provides automated runbooks for common operational tasks and incident response, integrating with AWS services?", "options": ["A. AWS CodeDeploy", "B. AWS Systems Manager Automation", "C. AWS OpsWorks", "D. AWS Step Functions"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Systems Manager Automation provides pre-built and custom runbooks (SSM documents) for operational tasks like patching, snapshot creation, and incident remediation, with approval workflows and audit trails."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "What is the purpose of the CodeDeploy appspec.yml file?", "options": ["A. Defines the CodePipeline stages and actions", "B. Specifies CloudFormation resources to create", "C. Defines deployment lifecycle hooks and file mappings for CodeDeploy", "D. Configures CodeBuild build environment"], "answer": 2, "explain": "appspec.yml is CodeDeploy's deployment specification file. It defines where application files are copied on the instance and which scripts run during each deployment lifecycle event."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "You need to capture all API calls to an S3 bucket used for financial records for forensic audit purposes. Which CloudTrail setting is required?", "options": ["A. Enable Management Events for S3", "B. Enable Data Events for the S3 bucket in CloudTrail", "C. Enable S3 server access logging", "D. Enable AWS Config on S3"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CloudTrail Data Events log object-level operations (GetObject, PutObject, DeleteObject) on S3. Management Events only log bucket-level control plane operations. Both are needed for complete S3 audit trails."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "A CloudFormation stack has a resource in UPDATE_ROLLBACK_FAILED state. What is the recommended recovery action?", "options": ["A. Delete and recreate the entire stack", "B. Use ContinueUpdateRollback API, optionally skipping the problematic resource", "C. Manually update the resource to match the previous state", "D. Contact AWS Support to reset the stack state"], "answer": 1, "explain": "ContinueUpdateRollback retries the rollback. You can specify resources to skip if they're blocking rollback, fixing them manually afterward. This avoids losing the entire stack."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "A company uses AWS OpsWorks Stacks to manage their application. They want to customize software installation using Chef recipes. At which OpsWorks lifecycle event should installation recipes be assigned?", "options": ["A. Setup", "B. Configure", "C. Deploy", "D. Undeploy"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The Setup event runs when an instance finishes booting. Assign installation and configuration recipes here to set up the instance environment before it starts serving traffic."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "Which AWS Systems Manager capability allows you to run commands across a fleet of EC2 instances without SSH access?", "options": ["A. Systems Manager Session Manager", "B. Systems Manager Run Command", "C. Systems Manager Patch Manager", "D. Systems Manager State Manager"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Run Command executes scripts or commands on managed instances without requiring SSH or RDP. It uses the SSM Agent and IAM for authentication, providing an auditable, secure alternative to SSH."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "A company needs centralized logging across 50 AWS accounts. What is the recommended architecture?", "options": ["A. Enable CloudWatch Logs in each account and query separately", "B. Use CloudWatch Logs cross-account subscription filters to stream logs to a central Security account", "C. Install Splunk on EC2 in each account", "D. Use S3 cross-region replication for log files"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Cross-account CloudWatch Logs subscription filters stream log data to a central account's Kinesis Data Streams or Firehose, enabling centralized log aggregation and analysis at scale."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "Which Systems Manager document type is used for defining automation workflows with multiple steps?", "options": ["A. Command documents (AWS-RunShellScript)", "B. Automation documents (aws:executeAwsApi, aws:runInstances)", "C. Session documents", "D. Package documents"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Automation documents define multi-step operational workflows using actions like aws:executeAwsApi, aws:runCommand, and aws:waitForAwsResourceProperty. They're used for complex remediation and operational procedures."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "How should service-level objectives (SLOs) be defined for multi-region deployments?", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "A CloudFormation template needs to store and manage secrets like database passwords securely. What is the best practice?", "options": ["A. Store secrets in plaintext in template parameters", "B. Use AWS Secrets Manager and reference in template", "C. Hardcode secrets in template", "D. Store in S3"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Secrets should be stored in AWS Secrets Manager or Parameter Store and referenced in CloudFormation, never embedded in templates."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "A company uses SAM for serverless applications. What advantage does SAM provide?", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "Your team needs to search through millions of log entries to find errors between specific timestamps. What CloudWatch feature enables this?", "options": ["A. CloudWatch Metrics", "B. CloudWatch Logs Insights for querying and analyzing logs", "C. CloudWatch Dashboards", "D. CloudWatch Alarms"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CloudWatch Logs Insights allows querying log data with a SQL-like syntax to find and analyze specific patterns across large datasets."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "An organization needs to implement chaos engineering to test application resilience. Which AWS service supports controlled fault injection?", "options": ["A. AWS X-Ray", "B. Amazon CloudWatch Synthetics", "C. AWS Fault Injection Simulator (FIS)", "D. AWS Systems Manager Run Command"], "answer": 2, "explain": "AWS FIS runs controlled fault injection experiments (terminating instances, throttling APIs, injecting CPU stress) to test how applications respond to failures, validating resilience before real incidents occur."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "A security incident reveals that an IAM access key was exposed in a public GitHub repository. What is the correct immediate response sequence?", "options": ["A. Delete the key → investigate what was accessed → notify management", "B. Deactivate the key → investigate CloudTrail logs for unauthorized activity → delete the key → rotate all potentially affected credentials", "C. Rotate the key → notify GitHub to remove the repository", "D. Change the IAM user password → enable MFA"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Immediately deactivating (not deleting) preserves the key for investigation while stopping access. CloudTrail analysis reveals what was accessed. Deletion comes after investigation. Other affected credentials may also need rotation."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "Multiple services across regions need to coordinate health status and failover decisions. What AWS service enables this?", "options": ["A. Route 53 only", "B. AWS Route 53 Application Recovery Controller for health awareness across regions", "C. CloudWatch only", "D. EventBridge"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Route 53 Application Recovery Controller monitors application readiness and data replication across regions, enabling coordinated failover."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "A CloudFormation stack deployment fails due to an IAM permission error. The stack rolls back. How do you identify the exact missing permission?", "options": ["A. Check CloudFormation events in the console", "B. Review CloudTrail for the AccessDenied event which shows the exact action and resource that was denied", "C. Check VPC Flow Logs", "D. Enable CloudFormation debug logging"], "answer": 1, "explain": "When CloudFormation receives an AccessDenied error, it's recorded in CloudTrail with the exact API action, resource ARN, and calling entity. This shows precisely which permission the CloudFormation service role is missing."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "An AWS Config rule detects that an EC2 instance is missing required security patches. How can remediation be automated?", "options": ["A. Manual patching", "B. Config Remediation Actions triggering Systems Manager Automation to apply patches", "C. Ignore the violation", "D. Manual notification"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS Config Remediation Actions automatically invoke Systems Manager Automation documents to fix violations like applying patches."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "A company needs to manage configuration parameters (like database endpoints) across multiple environments (dev/staging/prod) using Systems Manager. Which feature best supports this?", "options": ["A. SSM Parameter Store with path-based organization by environment (/myapp/dev/db-endpoint)", "B. SSM State Manager with environment tags", "C. SSM Run Command with environment parameters", "D. Systems Manager Inventory"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Parameter Store supports hierarchical paths (e.g., /myapp/prod/db-endpoint), enabling environment-specific configuration management. Applications retrieve their environment's parameters without code changes."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "What does the CodeDeploy deployment configuration 'Linear10PercentEvery10Minutes' mean?", "options": ["A. Deploy to 10% of instances every 10 minutes", "B. Shift 10% of traffic every 10 minutes to the new Lambda/ECS version", "C. Deploy for 10 minutes then pause for 10 minutes", "D. Allow 10 failures per 10-minute window"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Linear deployment configurations for Lambda/ECS shift traffic incrementally. Linear10PercentEvery10Minutes shifts 10% of traffic every 10 minutes until 100% reaches the new version."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "CodeBuild needs to access private Git repository during build. How can this be secured?", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "A company uses Ansible for configuration management. How can they integrate Ansible with AWS Systems Manager?", "options": ["A. Ansible cannot integrate with AWS Systems Manager", "B. Use SSM State Manager with the AWS-ApplyAnsiblePlaybooks association document", "C. Run Ansible from a dedicated EC2 control node only", "D. Convert all Ansible playbooks to Chef recipes for OpsWorks"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Systems Manager's AWS-ApplyAnsiblePlaybooks document runs Ansible playbooks on managed instances. State Manager associations can enforce Ansible configurations continuously across your fleet."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "A company's AWS account is showing unexpected charges for EC2 instances in regions they don't use. What is the first step?", "options": ["A. Terminate all instances immediately", "B. Enable CloudTrail and review API calls to identify who/what created the instances", "C. Call AWS Support", "D. Change the root account password"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CloudTrail captures who made API calls (including RunInstances). Reviewing CloudTrail logs identifies the IAM user, role, or external party that created unauthorized resources, providing evidence for incident response."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "A development team uses Git for version control and needs a managed Git repository solution on AWS. Which service integrates with CodePipeline for CI/CD?", "options": ["A. Amazon S3 for code storage", "B. AWS CodeCommit for Git repository management", "C. GitHub Enterprise within AWS", "D. AWS CodeBuild repository"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CodeCommit provides a managed Git repository service fully integrated with CodePipeline, supporting pull requests, branch protection, and native AWS integration."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "A company needs to verify that deployed applications meet compliance standards before production.", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "Your CodeBuild project needs to run different build steps depending on the Git branch.", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "Your organization is building serverless applications using Lambda and API Gateway. Which infrastructure-as-code framework allows Python to define these resources?", "options": ["A. AWS CloudFormation JSON templates", "B. AWS Serverless Application Model (SAM)", "C. AWS Cloud Development Kit (CDK)", "D. Terraform"], "answer": 2, "explain": "AWS CDK allows defining cloud infrastructure using programming languages like Python, TypeScript, or Java with higher-level abstractions than CloudFormation."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "An application's CloudWatch metric is not consistently breaching an alarm threshold but you suspect anomalous behavior. Which CloudWatch feature helps without defining fixed thresholds?", "options": ["A. CloudWatch Composite Alarms", "B. CloudWatch Anomaly Detection with ML-based alarm", "C. CloudWatch High Resolution Metrics", "D. CloudWatch Embedded Metrics Format"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CloudWatch Anomaly Detection uses ML to learn metric patterns and creates dynamic bands of expected values. Alarms based on anomaly detection fire when metrics fall outside the expected band without requiring fixed thresholds."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "Your organization wants to reduce risk during deployment by gradually shifting traffic to newly deployed application versions. Which CodeDeploy strategy minimizes blast radius?", "options": ["A. Canary deployment with gradual traffic shift", "B. In-place with immediate switch", "C. Blue/green with one-time cutover", "D. Linear deployment"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Canary deployments shift a small percentage of traffic to new versions first (e.g., 10% for 5 minutes), minimizing blast radius and allowing rollback if issues occur."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "Your application generates hundreds of thousands of log entries daily across multiple EC2 instances. What AWS service enables centralized collection?", "options": ["A. EC2 instance logs only", "B. CloudWatch Logs for centralized collection, storage, and querying", "C. S3 only", "D. CloudTrail"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CloudWatch Logs provides a centralized location for collecting, storing, and analyzing log data from various sources with long-term retention."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "An application uses SQS FIFO queue for ordered processing. To scale processing, you add more Lambda functions. What constraint must you be aware of?", "options": ["A. FIFO queues don't support Lambda triggers", "B. FIFO queues support up to 3,000 messages per second with batching; Lambda concurrency scales with message groups, not queue depth", "C. Each Lambda function processes messages from a different queue", "D. FIFO queues require manual polling from Lambda"], "answer": 1, "explain": "FIFO queue + Lambda event source mapping uses message group IDs to preserve ordering per group. Concurrency scales with the number of unique message group IDs, not total message volume. Max throughput is limited compared to standard queues."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "Which AWS service provides synthetic monitoring by running canary scripts to test application endpoints and APIs continuously?", "options": ["A. CloudWatch Container Insights", "B. AWS X-Ray active tracing", "C. CloudWatch Synthetics", "D. Route 53 health checks"], "answer": 2, "explain": "CloudWatch Synthetics runs canary scripts (Node.js or Python) on a schedule to simulate user interactions with APIs and UIs, detecting issues before real users are affected."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "An application writes structured JSON logs to CloudWatch Logs. How do you create a CloudWatch metric for the count of requests where 'status' field equals 'error'?", "options": ["A. Enable CloudWatch detailed metrics", "B. Create a CloudWatch Logs metric filter using JSON filter syntax { $.status = 'error' }", "C. Use X-Ray to count errors", "D. Parse logs manually with Athena"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CloudWatch Logs metric filters support JSON path syntax for structured logs. A filter matching { $.status = 'error' } increments a custom metric counter for each matching log line, enabling CloudWatch alarms on error rates."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "After a production incident, what is the primary purpose of a blameless post-mortem?", "options": ["A. Identify which team member made the mistake", "B. Understand systemic failures and implement process/technical improvements to prevent recurrence", "C. Document the incident for compliance audits", "D. Determine financial impact of the incident"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Blameless post-mortems focus on systemic issues and process improvements rather than individual blame. The goal is creating action items that reduce incident probability and improve detection/response time."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "What is an AWS CloudFormation Custom Resource, and when would you use one?", "options": ["A. A resource type for premium CloudFormation features", "B. A Lambda-backed resource that enables CloudFormation to manage resources not natively supported", "C. A CloudFormation macro for template transformation", "D. A CloudFormation resource import feature"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Custom Resources use Lambda functions to handle Create/Update/Delete lifecycle events, enabling CloudFormation to manage any resource (third-party services, legacy systems) as part of a stack."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "A CodeBuild project intermittently fails due to hitting Docker Hub rate limits when pulling base images. What is the most scalable solution?", "options": ["A. Add retry logic in buildspec.yml", "B. Use Amazon ECR to host approved base images and configure CodeBuild to use ECR", "C. Schedule builds during off-peak hours", "D. Purchase a Docker Hub Pro subscription"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Hosting base images in ECR eliminates Docker Hub rate limits, improves build reliability, and keeps images within your AWS environment for security and compliance."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "A Lambda function is experiencing cold start latency issues. Which X-Ray feature helps identify the source of latency in the function execution?", "options": ["A. X-Ray groups", "B. X-Ray service maps with trace analysis showing subsegment breakdown", "C. X-Ray sampling rules", "D. X-Ray encryption configuration"], "answer": 1, "explain": "X-Ray traces Lambda functions and creates subsegments for each code block and external call. The service map and trace timeline visually show where time is spent, including initialization (cold start) vs execution."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "A production deployment has caused errors. The CodeDeploy blue/green deployment is 20 minutes old. How do you roll back?", "options": ["A. Re-run the previous CodeDeploy deployment", "B. Use the CodeDeploy console to stop and roll back the current deployment", "C. Manually update the load balancer target group to point to old instances", "D. Terminate new instances and start old ones"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CodeDeploy provides a Stop and Roll Back option that reverts traffic to the original revision. For blue/green deployments within the termination wait period, the original fleet is still available."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "Your CodeBuild project needs to access a private npm registry that requires authentication. Where should you store the registry credentials?", "options": ["A. Hardcode them in the buildspec.yml file", "B. Store in AWS Secrets Manager and reference in buildspec.yml using environment variables", "C. Pass them as plaintext environment variables in CodeBuild project settings", "D. Store in an S3 bucket and download in the build phase"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Secrets Manager securely stores and rotates credentials. CodeBuild can reference secrets as environment variables, keeping credentials out of source code and build specs."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "A company wants to manage multiple EC2 instances' configuration state declaratively, ensuring Chef recipes are continuously applied. Which SSM feature does this?", "options": ["A. SSM Run Command with cron", "B. SSM State Manager associations", "C. SSM Patch Manager", "D. SSM Session Manager"], "answer": 1, "explain": "State Manager associations define desired configuration state and can apply Chef, Ansible, or PowerShell DSC configurations. They run on a schedule and re-apply if drift is detected."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "Your organization needs to manage CloudFormation stacks across multiple AWS accounts and regions. What is the recommended approach?", "options": ["A. Create individual stacks manually", "B. CloudFormation StackSets for automated multi-account, multi-region deployment", "C. Use AWS Organizations only", "D. Manual script for each account"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CloudFormation StackSets enable defining a stack once and deploying it across multiple accounts and regions, maintaining consistency and reducing manual effort."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "Which CodePipeline source action can detect changes in a GitHub repository without polling?", "options": ["A. GitHub (Version 1) action using OAuth", "B. GitHub (Version 2) action using CodeStar Connections", "C. S3 source action with GitHub integration", "D. CodeCommit with GitHub mirroring"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CodePipeline's GitHub (Version 2) action uses CodeStar Connections with webhooks for real-time change detection without polling, providing better reliability and security than OAuth-based V1 actions."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "A company has a critical API that must handle 99.99% availability. Which combination of AWS services best achieves this?", "options": ["A. Single EC2 instance with enhanced networking", "B. API Gateway + Lambda (serverless) with multi-region active-active using Route 53", "C. EC2 in one region with Auto Scaling", "D. Elastic Beanstalk with multi-AZ deployment"], "answer": 1, "explain": "API Gateway and Lambda are inherently multi-AZ and highly available within a region. Adding multi-region with Route 53 failover or latency routing achieves near-maximum availability for critical APIs."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "During a CodePipeline execution, the CodeBuild stage fails with a compilation error. What happens to the pipeline automatically?", "options": ["A. Pipeline continues to the next stage", "B. Pipeline stops; manual intervention or retry is needed", "C. Pipeline automatically rolls back to previous version", "D. Pipeline triggers a new commit to fix the error"], "answer": 1, "explain": "When a pipeline stage fails, execution halts and requires either manual approval to retry or manual intervention to proceed."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "Your AWS CDK application defines multiple Stacks with dependencies. How should cross-stack references be handled?", "options": ["A. Hard-code resource IDs between stacks", "B. Use stack outputs and cross-stack references with Fn::ImportValue", "C. Manual deployment order management", "D. Merge all resources into single stack"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CDK Stacks can reference outputs from other stacks; CloudFormation exports enable cross-stack references through Fn::ImportValue."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "Your CDK application uses third-party constructs that abstract CloudFormation resources.", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "A CloudFormation template has a Condition that determines whether to create a resource. If the condition is false, what happens to the resource?", "options": ["A. The resource is created with default values", "B. The resource is not created", "C. CloudFormation fails with an error", "D. The resource is created but disabled"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CloudFormation Conditions control whether resources, outputs, and properties are included in stack operations. If a condition evaluates to false, the associated resources are simply not created."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "Your application serves different geographic markets with strict data residency requirements.", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "An application uses SQS for async processing. Workers are failing to process messages, causing queue depth to grow. Which metric should you alarm on to detect this?", "options": ["A. NumberOfMessagesSent", "B. ApproximateAgeOfOldestMessage", "C. NumberOfMessagesDeleted", "D. ApproximateNumberOfMessagesVisible"], "answer": 1, "explain": "ApproximateAgeOfOldestMessage indicates how long messages are sitting unprocessed. A high value means workers are not keeping up. Alarming on this metric detects consumer lag more effectively than message count alone."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "An application uses SQS to decouple components. During peak load, processing falls behind but must eventually complete. Which SQS queue type is appropriate?", "options": ["A. FIFO queue with high throughput mode", "B. Standard queue with Auto Scaling based on queue depth", "C. Dead letter queue", "D. Delay queue"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Standard queues provide unlimited throughput. Auto Scaling consumers based on ApproximateNumberOfMessagesVisible ensures processing capacity scales with queue depth, providing elastic processing of peak loads."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "What does the CloudFormation WaitCondition resource type do?", "options": ["A. Pauses a stack update for manual approval", "B. Waits for a signal from an EC2 instance before continuing stack creation", "C. Checks if all resources in the stack are healthy", "D. Implements a polling loop for external dependencies"], "answer": 1, "explain": "WaitCondition pauses CloudFormation until an EC2 instance sends a success/failure signal (using cfn-signal). This ensures instance bootstrapping completes before CloudFormation marks it as done."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "In a CodeDeploy blue/green deployment to ECS, what happens to the original (blue) task set after successful deployment?", "options": ["A. It is immediately terminated", "B. It continues running alongside the green task set", "C. It is kept for the configured wait time then terminated, or you can terminate it manually", "D. It is automatically scaled down to 0"], "answer": 2, "explain": "After green task set validation, CodeDeploy waits for the configured termination wait time before terminating the original blue task set, allowing you to revert if needed during that window."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "Which EventBridge feature allows you to create a centralized event bus that receives events from multiple AWS accounts?", "options": ["A. EventBridge default event bus", "B. EventBridge custom event bus with resource-based policies allowing cross-account publishing", "C. EventBridge global endpoints", "D. EventBridge pipes"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Custom event buses support resource-based policies that allow other accounts to put events. This enables a centralized event bus pattern where a security or operations account receives events from all other accounts."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "A microservices application uses multiple CodePipeline pipelines. You need to ensure a shared library is built and tested before any dependent service pipeline runs. What is the best solution?", "options": ["A. Combine all pipelines into one large pipeline", "B. Use EventBridge to trigger dependent pipelines when the shared library pipeline succeeds", "C. Use CodeCommit triggers to start all pipelines simultaneously", "D. Schedule all pipelines with CloudWatch Events cron rules"], "answer": 1, "explain": "EventBridge can monitor CodePipeline state changes and trigger downstream pipelines, creating a pipeline-of-pipelines pattern while keeping each service pipeline independent."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "Which buildspec.yml phase runs commands to prepare the build environment, such as installing dependencies?", "options": ["A. pre_build", "B. build", "C. install", "D. post_build"], "answer": 2, "explain": "The install phase in buildspec.yml runs first and is designed for installing packages and dependencies in the build environment (e.g., npm install, pip install)."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "A Lambda function is failing due to a dependency service being unavailable. The function is configured to retry. How do you prevent retry storms during an outage?", "options": ["A. Disable Lambda retries", "B. Implement exponential backoff with jitter in the Lambda function, and use SQS with a dead-letter queue for async invocations", "C. Increase Lambda timeout to 15 minutes", "D. Use Lambda reserved concurrency to limit retries"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Exponential backoff with jitter prevents thundering herd on retry. DLQs capture failed async invocations for later processing. Together they provide resilient retry behavior without overwhelming a recovering dependency."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "A CloudFormation template references a secret value (like a password). What is the recommended approach to avoid hardcoding secrets?", "options": ["A. Encrypt the value in the template using KMS", "B. Use CloudFormation dynamic references to Secrets Manager or SSM Parameter Store SecureString", "C. Pass the secret as a template parameter", "D. Store secrets in the template Outputs section"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CloudFormation dynamic references ({{resolve:secretsmanager:...}} or {{resolve:ssm-secure:...}}) fetch secret values at deployment time without storing them in templates or parameters."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "Your organization needs to implement a multi-stage CI/CD pipeline that automatically builds, tests, and deploys applications across development, staging, and production environments. Which AWS service should orchestrate this workflow?", "options": ["A. AWS CodeBuild only", "B. AWS CodeDeploy for all stages", "C. AWS CodePipeline to orchestrate multiple stages", "D. AWS CodeCommit as the pipeline engine"], "answer": 2, "explain": "CodePipeline orchestrates the entire CI/CD workflow, coordinating CodeBuild for compilation/testing and CodeDeploy for deployment across multiple environments."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "Which CloudFormation feature allows you to reuse template fragments across multiple templates?", "options": ["A. CloudFormation Conditions", "B. Nested stacks using AWS::CloudFormation::Stack resource type", "C. CloudFormation Mappings", "D. CloudFormation Outputs with cross-stack references"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Nested stacks allow a parent stack to create child stacks, enabling reuse of common template components (networking, security groups) across multiple parent stacks."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "An application needs to process S3 events reliably. Direct S3 → Lambda invocation is losing events when Lambda is throttled. Which architecture improves reliability?", "options": ["A. Increase Lambda concurrency limit", "B. S3 → SQS → Lambda (event source mapping) for reliable event processing", "C. S3 → SNS → Lambda", "D. Use S3 Batch Operations instead"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Adding SQS between S3 and Lambda buffers events during throttling. The Lambda event source mapping retries failed messages and respects concurrency limits. SQS provides durability that direct invocation lacks."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "A company wants to prevent any CloudFormation stack from being deployed in regions other than us-east-1 and eu-west-1. How do they enforce this?", "options": ["A. Configure CloudFormation service endpoints", "B. Use AWS Organizations Service Control Policies (SCPs) to deny CloudFormation actions in non-approved regions", "C. Use IAM policies on all users", "D. Use CloudFormation StackSets with regional restrictions"], "answer": 1, "explain": "SCPs at the Organizations level apply to all accounts in the organization. Denying CloudFormation:CreateStack for all regions except approved ones prevents stacks from being deployed anywhere else."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "CloudFormation stack deletion should preserve certain resources like RDS databases.", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "A CloudFormation stack update fails midway. What is the default behavior?", "options": ["A. The stack is left in a partially updated state", "B. CloudFormation rolls back all changes to the previous working state", "C. CloudFormation retries the update automatically", "D. CloudFormation pauses and waits for manual intervention"], "answer": 1, "explain": "By default, CloudFormation rolls back all changes on stack update failure, restoring the stack to the last known stable state. You can disable rollback for debugging purposes."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "A company wants to receive real-time notifications when EC2 instances are terminated by Auto Scaling. Which AWS service should they use?", "options": ["A. CloudWatch Metrics with EC2 alarm", "B. Amazon EventBridge rule matching EC2 Auto Scaling lifecycle events", "C. CloudTrail with SNS notification", "D. EC2 instance health check"], "answer": 1, "explain": "EventBridge natively captures Auto Scaling lifecycle events (EC2 Instance Terminate Successful). Rules can route these events to SNS for notifications or Lambda for automated responses."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "A company needs to monitor custom application metrics (like active user sessions) in CloudWatch. Which approach is correct?", "options": ["A. Enable detailed monitoring on EC2 instances", "B. Use the CloudWatch PutMetricData API to publish custom metrics from the application", "C. Use CloudWatch Container Insights", "D. Enable VPC Flow Logs"], "answer": 1, "explain": "PutMetricData API allows applications to publish custom metrics to CloudWatch with custom namespaces, dimensions, and values, enabling monitoring of business and application-specific metrics."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "Your application runs on ECS Fargate and you need to collect container logs. What is the recommended approach?", "options": ["A. Install CloudWatch agent in each container", "B. Configure the awslogs log driver in the ECS task definition to send logs to CloudWatch Logs", "C. Use a sidecar container to forward logs", "D. Write logs to an EFS volume shared with CloudWatch"], "answer": 1, "explain": "ECS task definitions support the awslogs log driver, which automatically streams container stdout/stderr to a specified CloudWatch Logs group without any agent installation."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "You want to automatically create a new Elastic Beanstalk environment for each feature branch. Which approach best implements this GitOps pattern?", "options": ["A. Manually create environments for each branch", "B. Use CodePipeline with a Lambda function that creates/terminates EB environments based on branch events", "C. Use a single EB environment and deploy all branches there", "D. Use EC2 Auto Scaling to create environments"], "answer": 1, "explain": "A Lambda function triggered by CodeCommit branch events can use the EB API to create ephemeral environments per branch and clean them up on merge/delete, enabling true branch-based environments."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "A deployment pipeline needs to send different notifications based on pipeline stage (test failure vs production deployment). How do you implement stage-specific notifications?", "options": ["A. Use one SNS topic for all notifications", "B. Configure separate CodeStar Notifications rules per stage with different SNS topics and subscriber groups", "C. Use CloudWatch Events with manual filtering", "D. Send all notifications to one team email"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CodeStar Notifications supports granular event filtering per pipeline, stage, or action. Different SNS topics can route notifications to appropriate teams (dev team for test failures, ops team for production alerts)."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "A critical application must maintain zero data loss during an AZ failure. Which RDS configuration achieves this?", "options": ["A. RDS with automated backups every hour", "B. RDS Multi-AZ with synchronous replication to the standby", "C. RDS Read Replica with manual promotion", "D. Aurora with asynchronous cross-region replication"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Multi-AZ uses synchronous replication - writes are confirmed on both primary and standby before returning success. This means zero data loss (RPO=0) during AZ failure. Read replicas use asynchronous replication and may lag."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "CloudFormation drift detection identifies mismatches. How should this be remediated?", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "An RDS Multi-AZ deployment experiences a primary instance failure. What is the automatic behavior?", "options": ["A. RDS restores from the latest snapshot in 30-60 minutes", "B. RDS automatically promotes the standby replica to primary and updates the DNS endpoint within 60-120 seconds", "C. Applications must manually reconnect to the standby endpoint", "D. The primary is restarted automatically on the same instance"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Multi-AZ RDS maintains a synchronous standby. On primary failure, RDS automatically performs failover, promoting the standby and updating the CNAME DNS record. Applications using the endpoint reconnect automatically."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "What is the purpose of the CodeDeploy revision in an EC2/on-premises deployment?", "options": ["A. The IAM role used for deployment", "B. The application files and appspec.yml packaged together (in S3 or GitHub) that CodeDeploy deploys to instances", "C. The deployment configuration (OneAtATime, AllAtOnce)", "D. The target deployment group"], "answer": 1, "explain": "A CodeDeploy revision is the bundle of application content (code, scripts, config) and the appspec.yml file. It's stored in S3 or GitHub and represents the specific version being deployed."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "A company needs to ensure that code deployed to production has been scanned for security vulnerabilities. Where in the pipeline should this check occur?", "options": ["A. After deploying to production", "B. During the source stage in CodePipeline", "C. As a build or test stage before deployment, using tools like Amazon Inspector or SAST tools", "D. Only during manual code reviews"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Security scanning should block deployments before reaching production. Adding SAST/DAST scanning as a pipeline stage ensures vulnerabilities are caught before deployment, not after."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "CodePipeline integration with external systems (e.g., third-party code analysis).", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "An ECS Fargate task keeps failing to start due to an error pulling a private container image from ECR. What is the most likely cause?", "options": ["A. The ECR repository doesn't exist", "B. The ECS task execution role lacks ECR pull permissions (ecr:GetDownloadUrlForLayer, ecr:BatchGetImage)", "C. ECR is in the wrong region", "D. The container image tag doesn't exist"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Fargate uses the task execution role to pull images from ECR. Missing ECR permissions (GetDownloadUrlForLayer, BatchGetImage, GetAuthorizationToken) is the most common cause of image pull failures."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "An organization wants to ensure no CloudFormation stack is deployed without CloudTrail logging enabled. Which approach enforces this preventively?", "options": ["A. AWS Config rule that checks after deployment", "B. CloudFormation Guard (cfn-guard) policy-as-code rules run before deployment", "C. IAM policy restricting CloudFormation actions", "D. Manual template review process"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CloudFormation Guard provides policy-as-code rules that validate templates before deployment. Running cfn-guard in the CI/CD pipeline prevents non-compliant templates from being deployed."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "A company uses Jenkins for CI/CD but wants to integrate with AWS services. Which approach lets Jenkins deploy to AWS while maintaining centralized visibility?", "options": ["A. Replace Jenkins with CodePipeline entirely", "B. Use CodePipeline with a Jenkins custom action provider", "C. Migrate all Jenkins jobs to CodeBuild", "D. Use CloudFormation to manage Jenkins deployments"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CodePipeline has a Jenkins plugin that allows integrating Jenkins build/test stages into CodePipeline. This provides AWS-native visibility and integration while preserving existing Jenkins investments."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "A CloudFormation template creates an RDS database and an EC2 instance that connects to it. How do you ensure the RDS instance is created before the EC2 instance?", "options": ["A. List RDS before EC2 in the template", "B. Use the DependsOn attribute on the EC2 resource referencing the RDS resource", "C. Use separate stacks with cross-stack references", "D. CloudFormation automatically determines the correct order"], "answer": 3, "explain": "CloudFormation automatically determines resource creation order based on references (Ref, Fn::GetAtt). If EC2 uses Ref on the RDS instance, CloudFormation creates RDS first. DependsOn is needed for implicit dependencies."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "An EKS cluster's pods are consuming too much memory. Which CloudWatch feature provides container-level memory metrics without installing additional agents?", "options": ["A. CloudWatch default EC2 metrics", "B. CloudWatch Container Insights for EKS", "C. Custom metrics via PutMetricData in each pod", "D. CloudWatch agent on worker nodes only"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CloudWatch Container Insights for EKS collects cluster, node, pod, and container-level metrics automatically using a daemonset. It provides pre-built dashboards for cluster performance and resource utilization."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "A team wants to run database migration scripts as part of a CodeDeploy deployment but only once per deployment, not on every instance. How should they implement this?", "options": ["A. Run migrations in the BeforeInstall hook on all instances", "B. Run migrations in the BeforeInstall hook only on the first instance using an idempotent script", "C. Use a separate Lambda function triggered before CodeDeploy starts", "D. Run migrations manually before starting deployment"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Using a Lambda function or CodePipeline action to run migrations before CodeDeploy ensures migrations run exactly once, separated from instance-level deployment hooks."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "A company needs to visualize how API requests flow through microservices, showing dependencies and latency. What X-Ray feature provides this?", "options": ["A. X-Ray sampling rules", "B. X-Ray Service Map for visualizing service interactions", "C. X-Ray segments", "D. X-Ray alarms"], "answer": 1, "explain": "X-Ray Service Maps visualize how requests flow through services, showing dependencies, call counts, latency, and error rates."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "What is the difference between CloudFormation Stack Policies and IAM policies for CloudFormation?", "options": ["A. They are the same thing", "B. Stack Policies prevent specific resources in a stack from being accidentally updated/deleted; IAM policies control who can perform CloudFormation API actions", "C. Stack Policies control who can create stacks; IAM policies control what resources CloudFormation creates", "D. Stack Policies are for StackSets only"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Stack Policies are resource-level protections that prevent accidental updates to critical stack resources (like production databases). IAM policies control user/role permissions to perform CloudFormation API operations."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "A company wants to audit all changes to their AWS infrastructure resources over the past 90 days. Which service provides this configuration history?", "options": ["A. CloudTrail (shows API calls)", "B. AWS Config configuration history and configuration timeline", "C. CloudWatch Logs", "D. AWS Trusted Advisor"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS Config records configuration snapshots of resources over time. The configuration timeline shows how resource configurations changed, who changed them (via CloudTrail integration), and when changes occurred."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "A company wants to implement active-active multi-region deployment for their DynamoDB-backed application. Which DynamoDB feature enables this?", "options": ["A. DynamoDB Read Replicas", "B. DynamoDB Global Tables", "C. DynamoDB Streams with cross-region Lambda replication", "D. DynamoDB Accelerator (DAX)"], "answer": 1, "explain": "DynamoDB Global Tables provides fully managed, multi-region, multi-active replication. Writes in any region are replicated to all other regions within seconds, enabling true active-active deployments."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "A company wants to enforce consistent tagging on all CloudFormation-created resources. Which approach enforces this at the template level?", "options": ["A. Add tags manually to each resource", "B. Use CloudFormation stack-level tags that propagate to all supported resources", "C. Use Lambda to tag resources after stack creation", "D. Use AWS Config rules to detect untagged resources"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Stack-level tags defined in CloudFormation are automatically applied to all supported resources in the stack. This ensures consistent tagging without manually adding tags to each resource."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "A company runs a blue/green deployment using CodeDeploy on EC2. After deployment, they want to automatically run smoke tests and roll back if tests fail. Which feature enables this?", "options": ["A. CodeDeploy deployment groups with lifecycle hooks", "B. CloudWatch alarms with automatic rollback", "C. Lambda functions triggered by SNS", "D. CodePipeline approval actions"], "answer": 0, "explain": "CodeDeploy lifecycle hooks (AfterInstall, ApplicationStart, ValidateService) allow running custom scripts during deployment. If the ValidateService hook fails, CodeDeploy automatically rolls back."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "A CloudFormation template creates a VPC with subnets. You need the VPC CIDR to be different for dev vs prod. Which CloudFormation feature handles this most cleanly?", "options": ["A. Create separate templates for each environment", "B. Use CloudFormation Parameters with different parameter values per environment, or use CloudFormation Mappings", "C. Hardcode different CIDRs with conditions", "D. Use nested stacks with different VPC stacks"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Parameters allow passing environment-specific values at stack creation. Mappings provide a lookup table (e.g., environment → CIDR). Both approaches keep a single template with environment-specific values injected."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "A company wants to implement a warm standby DR strategy. What characterizes a warm standby?", "options": ["A. Complete idle environment with no running resources", "B. A scaled-down but fully functional copy of the production environment running continuously in the DR region", "C. DNS-based failover with no pre-existing DR resources", "D. Active-active deployment across two regions"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Warm standby runs a minimal but functional copy of production (scaled-down instances, smaller databases) continuously. Failover involves scaling up the DR environment to full capacity, achieving faster RTO than pilot light."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "CodeDeploy needs pre-deployment validation. Which AppSpec lifecycle event should define checks?", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "A team wants to detect when their application's error rate exceeds 5% over 5 minutes and automatically trigger a remediation Lambda function. How do you implement this?", "options": ["A. CloudWatch Alarm on error metric → SNS topic → Lambda subscription", "B. CloudWatch Events rule polling error logs every minute", "C. CloudWatch Logs Insights query running every 5 minutes", "D. X-Ray trace analysis with Lambda trigger"], "answer": 0, "explain": "CloudWatch Alarms monitor metrics and trigger SNS notifications. Lambda functions subscribed to the SNS topic receive the alert and can execute automated remediation actions."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "Which CloudFormation feature allows you to create a standard, approved set of resources that users can deploy without needing to write CloudFormation themselves?", "options": ["A. CloudFormation Macros", "B. AWS Service Catalog with CloudFormation templates", "C. CloudFormation StackSets", "D. CloudFormation Change Sets"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS Service Catalog lets administrators create portfolios of approved CloudFormation templates. End users can launch standardized products without needing CloudFormation knowledge or broad AWS permissions."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "You need to create an alarm that triggers only when multiple conditions are met.", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "A company needs to run automated security scans on newly launched EC2 instances within 5 minutes of launch. How do you implement this?", "options": ["A. Schedule Inspector scans daily", "B. EventBridge rule detects EC2 RunInstances event → Lambda triggers Amazon Inspector assessment", "C. Manually trigger Inspector scans after each launch", "D. Use Systems Manager to scan instances on boot"], "answer": 1, "explain": "EventBridge captures EC2 RunInstances events in near-real-time. A Lambda function can immediately trigger an Inspector assessment or SSM security scan on the new instance, providing fast automated security validation."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "A company needs to ensure all EC2 instances in an Auto Scaling group have the same software configuration applied automatically when new instances launch. Which approach is most scalable?", "options": ["A. Manually configure each new instance", "B. Use EC2 User Data with a bootstrap script", "C. Use Systems Manager State Manager associations to apply desired configurations", "D. Both B and C are appropriate; C is preferred for ongoing compliance enforcement"], "answer": 3, "explain": "User Data runs once at launch but doesn't enforce ongoing compliance. State Manager associations continuously enforce desired state, reapplying configuration on drift detection. Both can work together."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "Which CodePipeline stage type allows you to invoke a Lambda function as a custom pipeline action?", "options": ["A. Source", "B. Build", "C. Invoke", "D. Deploy"], "answer": 2, "explain": "CodePipeline's Invoke action type executes Lambda functions as pipeline stages. The Lambda function receives pipeline information, performs custom logic, and signals success or failure back to CodePipeline."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "Which metric should you monitor to detect memory pressure on EC2 instances running application servers?", "options": ["A. CPUUtilization from CloudWatch default metrics", "B. mem_used_percent from CloudWatch agent custom metrics", "C. NetworkIn/NetworkOut metrics", "D. DiskReadOps metrics"], "answer": 1, "explain": "EC2 default metrics don't include memory. The CloudWatch agent must be installed to collect memory metrics (mem_used_percent) and stream them to CloudWatch as custom metrics."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "A production database migration is failing and causing extended downtime. What should be your first action according to incident response best practices?", "options": ["A. Debug the migration script to find the root cause", "B. Communicate the incident status to stakeholders and roll back to restore service", "C. Escalate to the database vendor", "D. Run the migration again with verbose logging"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Incident response prioritizes restoring service over finding root cause. Rolling back to the working state stops the bleeding. Post-incident, you investigate root cause in a non-production environment."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "How can you prevent a CodePipeline pipeline from being disabled or modified by developers without DevOps approval?", "options": ["A. Use S3 bucket policies on the artifact bucket", "B. Use IAM policies to restrict codepipeline:UpdatePipeline and codepipeline:DisablePipelineStage actions", "C. Enable MFA on all developer accounts", "D. Use AWS Config to monitor pipeline changes"], "answer": 1, "explain": "IAM policies can restrict specific CodePipeline API actions. Restricting UpdatePipeline, DisablePipelineStage, and DeletePipeline prevents unauthorized modifications to production pipelines."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "A company wants to achieve RPO of 1 hour and RTO of 4 hours for their application. Which DR strategy meets these requirements at the lowest cost?", "options": ["A. Multi-site active/active", "B. Warm standby", "C. Backup and restore", "D. Pilot light"], "answer": 3, "explain": "Pilot light maintains a minimal running version of the environment (core infrastructure on, application off). RTO is hours (starting the application), RPO depends on replication frequency. Lower cost than warm standby."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "A team uses AWS Systems Manager OpsCenter to manage operational issues. How are OpsItems typically created?", "options": ["A. Manually created by engineers", "B. Automatically from CloudWatch alarms, EventBridge rules, and AWS services like Config and GuardDuty", "C. Only from CloudTrail events", "D. Only from AWS Support tickets"], "answer": 1, "explain": "OpsCenter integrates with CloudWatch alarms, EventBridge, Config, GuardDuty, and other services to automatically create OpsItems when issues are detected, enabling faster response with context and runbooks."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "Your CDK application has complex logic for resource creation. How should this complexity be managed?", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "A team uses AWS CDK v2. How does CDK synthesize and deploy infrastructure?", "options": ["A. CDK writes directly to AWS APIs without CloudFormation", "B. CDK app synth generates CloudFormation templates, which are then deployed via CloudFormation", "C. CDK deploys Terraform configurations", "D. CDK uses AWS CLI to make direct API calls"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CDK synthesizes application code into CloudFormation templates (cdk synth). CDK deploy then submits these templates to CloudFormation, combining the developer experience of programming languages with CloudFormation's reliability."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "CloudTrail is enabled but you notice API calls made through the AWS Console are not appearing in the logs. What is the most likely cause?", "options": ["A. CloudTrail only logs CLI API calls", "B. The CloudTrail trail is configured to log only Data Events, not Management Events", "C. Console actions are logged by CloudWatch, not CloudTrail", "D. There is a 15-minute delay in CloudTrail log delivery"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CloudTrail trails log Management Events (control plane) and Data Events (data plane) separately. Console actions are Management Events. If only Data Events are enabled, console API calls won't appear."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "A company wants to implement canary deployments for a Lambda function. Which approach provides built-in canary routing?", "options": ["A. Create two Lambda functions and use Route 53 weighted routing", "B. Use Lambda function aliases with traffic shifting via CodeDeploy", "C. Use API Gateway canary release deployments only", "D. Implement custom routing logic in Lambda"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Lambda aliases support traffic shifting, and CodeDeploy can manage canary deployments by gradually shifting traffic from the old version to the new one with automatic rollback on CloudWatch alarms."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "An EC2 instance running an application needs a configuration file updated whenever a Parameter Store value changes. How do you implement live configuration refresh?", "options": ["A. Restart the instance on every change", "B. Use Systems Manager AppConfig with polling or change notification from Parameter Store via EventBridge → Lambda → AppConfig rollout", "C. Manually update the file via SSH", "D. Use CloudWatch to detect parameter changes"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AppConfig provides controlled configuration deployment with validation and rollback. EventBridge detects Parameter Store changes, triggering configuration updates to running instances without restarts."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "A team wants to automatically trigger a CodePipeline pipeline when a developer pushes code to a specific branch in CodeCommit. What is the recommended approach?", "options": ["A. Poll CodeCommit every minute using a Lambda function", "B. Use Amazon EventBridge rule to detect CodeCommit repository state change events", "C. Configure a CloudWatch alarm on CodeCommit metrics", "D. Use SNS to notify CodePipeline directly"], "answer": 1, "explain": "EventBridge (formerly CloudWatch Events) natively integrates with CodeCommit to trigger pipelines on push events, providing real-time, event-driven pipeline execution."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "Which CloudWatch feature creates real-time dashboards showing which contributors are causing high resource utilization (e.g., top bandwidth consumers)?", "options": ["A. CloudWatch Log Insights", "B. CloudWatch Contributor Insights", "C. CloudWatch Anomaly Detection", "D. CloudWatch ServiceLens"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Contributor Insights analyzes log data to identify top contributors to system performance issues (e.g., which IPs use the most bandwidth, which users make the most errors)."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "A team needs to share CloudFormation Outputs between stacks. Which function retrieves values exported from another stack?", "options": ["A. Fn::GetAtt with cross-stack reference", "B. Fn::ImportValue", "C. Ref with stack name", "D. Fn::Sub with export name"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Fn::ImportValue retrieves values exported by other stacks using Export/Output. This enables loose coupling between stacks while sharing resource references like VPC IDs or security group IDs."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "Which CloudWatch feature allows you to analyze log data using SQL-like queries to identify patterns and troubleshoot issues?", "options": ["A. CloudWatch Metrics", "B. CloudWatch Log Insights", "C. CloudWatch Contributor Insights", "D. CloudWatch Synthetics"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CloudWatch Logs Insights provides an interactive query interface with a SQL-like language for analyzing log data, calculating statistics, and visualizing trends across log groups."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "A company's application must continue functioning even if AWS us-east-1 becomes completely unavailable. Which Route 53 routing policy enables this failover?", "options": ["A. Weighted routing with equal weights", "B. Latency-based routing", "C. Failover routing with health checks on primary and secondary regions", "D. Geolocation routing"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Route 53 Failover routing continuously health-checks the primary endpoint and automatically routes to the secondary region if the primary fails, enabling cross-region disaster recovery."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "What does AWS CloudFormation Drift Detection identify?", "options": ["A. Performance degradation in CloudFormation deployments", "B. Differences between the current state of stack resources and the expected state defined in the template", "C. Security vulnerabilities in CloudFormation templates", "D. Unused resources in a CloudFormation stack"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Drift Detection compares actual resource configurations against the CloudFormation template. Drifted resources indicate manual changes were made outside CloudFormation, breaking IaC consistency."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "A company wants to enforce that all CodePipeline pipelines must have a manual approval stage before production deployment. How do you enforce this at scale?", "options": ["A. Train developers on the policy", "B. Use AWS Config rule to detect non-compliant pipelines and alert via SNS", "C. Restrict IAM permissions to only allow manual approval pipeline creation", "D. Use Service Control Policies to block pipeline creation without approval stages"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS Config can evaluate CodePipeline configurations against custom rules. Non-compliant pipelines (missing approval) can trigger SNS notifications or auto-remediation."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "You need to automatically remediate non-compliant EC2 instances (e.g., missing required tags) detected by AWS Config. What is the recommended approach?", "options": ["A. Manually review Config findings and fix them", "B. Configure AWS Config remediation actions using Systems Manager Automation documents", "C. Use CloudWatch Alarms to alert the team", "D. Write custom Lambda functions for each Config rule"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS Config supports automatic remediation using Systems Manager Automation runbooks. When a rule detects non-compliance, it automatically triggers the remediation action to correct the configuration."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "A database needs to be replicated across regions for disaster recovery with minimal recovery time objective (RTO). What Aurora feature supports this?", "options": ["A. Backup and restore", "B. Aurora Global Database with read-only secondaries for instant failover", "C. Snapshots only", "D. Manual replication"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Aurora Global Database replicates data across regions, allowing secondary regions to be promoted for instant failover with near-zero RTO."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "A company wants to detect when an IAM user makes console login attempts from an unusual geographic location. Which service detects this behavior automatically?", "options": ["A. CloudTrail with manual log analysis", "B. Amazon GuardDuty", "C. AWS Config", "D. CloudWatch Logs with metric filters"], "answer": 1, "explain": "GuardDuty uses ML to detect anomalous behavior including unusual API activity, impossible travel scenarios, and credential abuse, alerting on suspicious login patterns automatically."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "A CloudFormation template needs to reference Parameter Store values dynamically.", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "A CloudFormation stack update fails because resource replacement would cause downtime.", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "A CodeBuild project needs to build Docker images and push to ECR. Which permissions does the CodeBuild IAM role require?", "options": ["A. AmazonEC2ContainerRegistryFullAccess", "B. ecr:GetAuthorizationToken, ecr:BatchCheckLayerAvailability, ecr:InitiateLayerUpload, ecr:UploadLayerPart, ecr:CompleteLayerUpload, ecr:PutImage", "C. AWSCodeBuildAdminAccess", "D. AdministratorAccess"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Pushing images to ECR requires specific ECR API permissions for authentication and layer upload. The principle of least privilege means granting only these specific ECR actions rather than full ECR access."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "What is the purpose of a CloudFormation Change Set?", "options": ["A. Automatically apply infrastructure changes on a schedule", "B. Preview the changes CloudFormation will make before executing a stack update", "C. Roll back a failed stack update", "D. Import existing resources into a CloudFormation stack"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Change Sets show a preview of proposed changes (Add/Modify/Remove) before executing. This lets you verify that intended changes are correct and identify unintended modifications."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "A DevOps team wants to track mean time to recovery (MTTR) for their incidents. Which AWS service helps measure and report on this operational metric?", "options": ["A. CloudWatch Metrics with custom MTTR metric", "B. Systems Manager Incident Manager with post-incident analysis reports", "C. AWS Health Dashboard", "D. AWS Trusted Advisor"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Incident Manager tracks incident start/resolution times automatically. Its post-incident analysis provides metrics including time to detect and time to resolve, helping teams measure and improve MTTR over time."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "Which AWS service provides a centralized incident management platform with runbooks, escalation, and communication tools?", "options": ["A. AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager", "B. AWS OpsWorks", "C. Amazon Connect", "D. AWS Service Catalog"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Systems Manager Incident Manager provides incident response features including automated runbooks, escalation plans, chat channels, and post-incident analysis, integrating natively with CloudWatch alarms and EventBridge."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "Your team wants to define infrastructure using object-oriented programming concepts. Which approach is most suitable?", "options": ["A. CloudFormation JSON templates", "B. AWS Cloud Development Kit (CDK)", "C. AWS SAM", "D. Manual provisioning"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS CDK enables programming language features including classes, interfaces, and composition for defining infrastructure reusably."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "Your CodeBuild builds run for 45 minutes but most of the time is spent downloading the same dependencies. How do you speed up builds?", "options": ["A. Upgrade to a larger CodeBuild instance type", "B. Enable CodeBuild caching (S3 or local cache) for dependencies", "C. Use a custom Docker image with pre-installed dependencies in ECR", "D. Both B and C are valid approaches"], "answer": 3, "explain": "Both S3/local caching for dependency directories AND custom Docker images with pre-installed dependencies reduce build time. Custom images provide the most consistent cache, while S3 caching handles dynamic dependencies."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "During an incident, an EC2 instance needs forensic analysis but must not be terminated by Auto Scaling. What do you do first?", "options": ["A. Stop the instance", "B. Enable Scale-In Protection on the instance and detach it from the load balancer", "C. Take a snapshot and terminate the instance", "D. Remove the instance from the Auto Scaling group"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Scale-In Protection prevents Auto Scaling from terminating the instance. Detaching from the load balancer stops new traffic. The instance can then be analyzed via Session Manager without risk of Auto Scaling termination."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "Your Elastic Beanstalk application needs zero-downtime deployments. Which deployment policy should you choose?", "options": ["A. All at once", "B. Rolling", "C. Rolling with additional batch", "D. Immutable"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Rolling with additional batch launches new instances before removing old ones, ensuring full capacity is maintained throughout deployment with no downtime."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "A company's ECS service is experiencing container crashes. How do you implement automatic recovery?", "options": ["A. Set up CloudWatch alarms to notify the on-call team", "B. Configure ECS Service desired count; ECS automatically replaces unhealthy tasks", "C. Use EC2 Auto Scaling to replace instances", "D. Manually restart failed containers via ECS console"], "answer": 1, "explain": "ECS Services maintain the desired task count. When containers fail health checks or crash, ECS automatically launches replacement tasks. Container-level health checks detect crashes faster than instance-level checks."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "Which service provides a GitOps-style approach to managing Kubernetes applications on Amazon EKS using a declarative configuration model?", "options": ["A. AWS CodeDeploy with ECS provider", "B. AWS App Mesh", "C. AWS Controllers for Kubernetes (ACK) or Flux/ArgoCD on EKS", "D. AWS OpsWorks Stacks"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Flux and ArgoCD are GitOps tools that continuously reconcile Kubernetes cluster state with Git. ACK also provides Kubernetes-native AWS resource management. These enable declarative, Git-driven EKS management."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "An EC2 instance becomes unresponsive due to a runaway process. The instance has no SSH access configured. How do you recover it without terminating?", "options": ["A. Terminate and replace the instance", "B. Use Systems Manager Session Manager to connect and kill the process", "C. Reboot via EC2 console", "D. Create an AMI and launch a new instance"], "answer": 1, "explain": "SSM Session Manager provides browser-based shell access to EC2 instances without SSH keys or security group rules. You can connect to unresponsive instances to diagnose and fix issues interactively."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "A company wants to implement connection pooling for their Aurora database to handle thousands of concurrent connections from Lambda functions. Which service provides this?", "options": ["A. ElastiCache Redis as a connection proxy", "B. Amazon RDS Proxy", "C. Aurora Auto Scaling", "D. VPC Security Groups limiting connections"], "answer": 1, "explain": "RDS Proxy maintains a pool of database connections and multiplexes them across Lambda functions. This dramatically reduces database connections (Lambda creates one per invocation) and improves resilience during failovers."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "A DevOps engineer needs to monitor the number of failed login attempts across all EC2 instances running Linux. Which approach works without SSH access?", "options": ["A. Query each instance via Systems Manager Run Command", "B. Use CloudWatch agent to collect /var/log/secure and create metric filters for failed logins", "C. Enable VPC Flow Logs and filter for SSH traffic", "D. Use GuardDuty SSH finding reports"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The CloudWatch agent streams log files to CloudWatch Logs. A metric filter on the log group can count 'Failed password' entries and publish a CloudWatch metric, enabling alerting on brute force attempts."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "CodeBuild reports build failures due to timeout. What strategies can optimize build time?", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "Your X-Ray traces are too verbose and analyzing all data is expensive. How can you reduce costs while maintaining visibility?", "options": ["A. Disable X-Ray tracing", "B. Implement X-Ray sampling rules to sample a percentage of requests", "C. Stop collecting traces", "D. Manual sampling"], "answer": 1, "explain": "X-Ray sampling rules allow configuring what percentage of requests are traced, reducing costs while maintaining visibility into application behavior."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "A developer needs to test changes locally before pushing to CodeCommit. Which tool allows running CodeBuild builds locally?", "options": ["A. AWS CLI with codebuild start-build --local flag", "B. CodeBuild local agent Docker container", "C. AWS SAM CLI for CodeBuild", "D. CodeBuild cannot run locally"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS provides a CodeBuild local agent as a Docker container that replicates the CodeBuild environment locally, enabling developers to debug build issues without incurring build costs."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "EventBridge needs to send events to multiple targets with different transformations.", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "What is the difference between CodeDeploy in-place and blue/green deployment?", "options": ["A. In-place is for EC2, blue/green is for Lambda only", "B. In-place updates existing instances; blue/green provisions new instances alongside old ones then switches traffic", "C. Blue/green is faster but more expensive; in-place is safer", "D. There is no difference in EC2 deployments"], "answer": 1, "explain": "In-place deployment stops the application, deploys, and restarts on existing instances (causing downtime). Blue/green provisions new instances with the new version and shifts traffic, maintaining the old fleet for rollback."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "A CodeBuild build needs to access resources in a private VPC (like an RDS database). What must be configured?", "options": ["A. VPC peering between CodeBuild and the VPC", "B. CodeBuild VPC configuration specifying VPC, subnets, and security groups", "C. NAT Gateway with CodeBuild IP whitelist", "D. VPN connection to CodeBuild service"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CodeBuild supports running builds inside a VPC by specifying the VPC ID, subnets, and security groups in the CodeBuild project configuration, enabling access to private resources."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "CodeBuild caching can significantly improve build performance. What does it store?", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "A team needs to store and share private npm packages across multiple CodeBuild projects. Which service provides a managed private package repository?", "options": ["A. S3 with a custom npm registry configuration", "B. AWS CodeArtifact", "C. ECR with npm translation", "D. CodeCommit as a package store"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CodeArtifact is a fully managed artifact repository that supports npm, PyPI, Maven, and other package formats. It provides private package hosting and proxies public registries like npmjs.com."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "What is the maximum number of stacks that CloudFormation StackSets can deploy to simultaneously in a stack operation?", "options": ["A. 10 accounts at a time", "B. Configurable via MaxConcurrentPercentage or MaxConcurrentCount", "C. 100 stacks total", "D. 1 region at a time"], "answer": 1, "explain": "StackSets deployment concurrency is configurable. You can specify MaxConcurrentCount (number of accounts) or MaxConcurrentPercentage (percentage of target accounts) to control parallel deployment speed."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "A team wants to automatically invalidate CloudFront cache after each CodeDeploy deployment to EC2. What is the most efficient approach?", "options": ["A. Manually invalidate via AWS Console after each deployment", "B. Add a CodeDeploy AfterAllowTraffic lifecycle hook that calls CloudFront CreateInvalidation API", "C. Schedule CloudFront invalidation every 30 minutes", "D. Set very low TTL values on all CloudFront behaviors"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The AfterAllowTraffic hook runs after traffic is shifted to the new deployment. A script or Lambda calling the CloudFront CreateInvalidation API ensures stale content is purged automatically as part of the deployment."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "An application uses ElastiCache Redis for session management. To ensure sessions persist during a Redis node failure, what should you configure?", "options": ["A. ElastiCache Redis single node with snapshots", "B. ElastiCache Redis Multi-AZ with automatic failover", "C. Use DynamoDB instead of Redis for sessions", "D. Write sessions to S3"], "answer": 1, "explain": "ElastiCache Redis Multi-AZ maintains a synchronous replica. On primary failure, automatic failover promotes the replica within 60 seconds, preserving session data with minimal disruption."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "Your application serves users globally and needs to provide low-latency access from any region. What Route 53 routing strategy achieves this?", "options": ["A. Simple routing", "B. Weighted routing", "C. Latency-based routing directing users to nearest healthy endpoint", "D. Geolocation routing"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Route 53 latency-based routing automatically directs users to the endpoint with lowest latency, providing optimal user experience globally."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "A company's ALB access logs show intermittent 502 errors. Which combination of tools best helps identify the root cause?", "options": ["A. CloudWatch metrics only", "B. ALB access logs in Athena for error pattern analysis + X-Ray traces for downstream service failures", "C. Enable Enhanced Monitoring on EC2 instances", "D. Review CloudTrail API logs"], "answer": 1, "explain": "ALB access logs (queried via Athena) reveal error patterns and request details. X-Ray traces show which downstream service (ECS, Lambda, EC2) is returning errors, providing end-to-end visibility for 502 troubleshooting."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "A company's EC2 instances in an Auto Scaling group are experiencing health check failures, causing constant instance replacement. How do you diagnose this without disrupting the scaling group?", "options": ["A. Disable health checks temporarily", "B. Put the instance in Standby state to investigate without triggering replacement", "C. Terminate all instances and start fresh", "D. Increase the health check grace period to 1 hour"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Auto Scaling Standby state removes an instance from service (stops health checks and load balancing) while keeping it running and accessible for investigation. The instance can be returned to service after diagnosis."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "A team wants to implement feature flags in their CI/CD pipeline without redeploying the application. Which AWS service best supports this?", "options": ["A. AWS CodeDeploy deployment configurations", "B. AWS AppConfig for feature flag management", "C. AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store with manual updates", "D. Environment variables in Elastic Beanstalk"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS AppConfig provides feature flag management with safe deployment strategies, validators, and rollback capabilities, allowing runtime configuration changes without application redeployment."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "Incident response metrics show automated remediation is failing for certain violations.", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "A company has a multi-tier application. The web tier is in an Auto Scaling group behind an ALB. Which configuration ensures high availability across Availability Zones?", "options": ["A. Deploy all instances in a single AZ for lower latency", "B. Span the Auto Scaling group across multiple AZs with equal AZ distribution and ALB configured for all AZs", "C. Use placement groups to keep instances close together", "D. Use a single large instance instead of multiple small ones"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Spanning multiple AZs ensures the application survives AZ failures. The ALB distributes traffic and the Auto Scaling group maintains capacity across AZs, providing true high availability."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "An application needs to track distributed requests across multiple microservices to identify performance bottlenecks. Which AWS service is designed for this?", "options": ["A. CloudWatch Logs", "B. CloudTrail", "C. AWS X-Ray for distributed request tracing", "D. EventBridge"], "answer": 2, "explain": "AWS X-Ray traces requests across distributed applications, showing service interactions, latency, and errors in end-to-end transaction flows."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "Your organization needs to manage CloudFormation stacks across multiple AWS accounts.", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "An application is receiving traffic spikes causing Lambda function throttling. How do you implement automatic scaling to handle spikes?", "options": ["A. Increase Lambda memory allocation", "B. Use Lambda Reserved Concurrency to guarantee capacity", "C. Use Lambda Provisioned Concurrency to pre-warm instances", "D. Both B and C address different aspects; Provisioned handles cold starts, Reserved guarantees allocation"], "answer": 3, "explain": "Provisioned Concurrency pre-initializes Lambda instances to eliminate cold starts during spikes. Reserved Concurrency guarantees a portion of account concurrency for critical functions. Together they address throttling and latency."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "Which service provides a managed source control service that is compatible with Git and integrates natively with other AWS developer tools?", "options": ["A. GitHub Enterprise", "B. AWS CodeCommit", "C. AWS CodeArtifact", "D. AWS S3 with versioning"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CodeCommit is AWS's managed Git repository service. It integrates natively with CodeBuild, CodeDeploy, and CodePipeline, and supports IAM-based authentication."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "A CloudFormation stack deployment is causing issues in production. The stack has DeletionPolicy:Retain on critical resources. What happens if you delete the stack?", "options": ["A. All resources are deleted including retained ones", "B. Critical resources are retained (not deleted) when the stack is deleted", "C. The stack deletion fails", "D. Resources with Retain policy are moved to another stack"], "answer": 1, "explain": "DeletionPolicy:Retain causes CloudFormation to remove the resource from the stack but not delete the actual AWS resource. This protects critical data (RDS, S3) from accidental deletion during stack rollbacks or deletions."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "A company wants to be notified when their AWS bill is projected to exceed $10,000 for the month. How do you configure this?", "options": ["A. Create a CloudWatch billing alarm on EstimatedCharges metric", "B. Set up AWS Budgets with an alert threshold and email notification", "C. Check Cost Explorer daily", "D. Use Cost Anomaly Detection with SNS"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS Budgets allows creating cost budgets with alert thresholds. When actual or forecasted costs exceed the threshold, Budgets sends notifications via SNS or email, enabling proactive cost management."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "Your CodePipeline needs to deploy to multiple AWS accounts (dev, staging, prod). What is the recommended cross-account deployment approach?", "options": ["A. Use the same IAM user credentials across all accounts", "B. Store credentials for each account in Secrets Manager", "C. Configure cross-account IAM roles and use CodePipeline's cross-account action provider", "D. Create separate pipelines in each account"], "answer": 2, "explain": "CodePipeline supports cross-account deployments using IAM roles. The pipeline assumes a role in the target account, providing secure, auditable cross-account deployments following the principle of least privilege."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "A distributed application uses multiple Lambda functions. A customer reports a slow transaction. How do you trace the full request across all Lambda functions?", "options": ["A. Enable CloudWatch detailed logging on all Lambda functions", "B. Use AWS X-Ray distributed tracing with trace IDs propagated across service calls", "C. Check CloudWatch Logs for each Lambda function separately", "D. Use VPC Flow Logs to trace network packets"], "answer": 1, "explain": "X-Ray creates traces that follow requests across service boundaries using trace IDs. The service map shows the full request path with latency at each hop, enabling end-to-end troubleshooting."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "Your application experiences a sudden performance degradation. How should monitoring and alerting be integrated to detect and respond automatically?", "options": ["A. Manual monitoring only", "B. CloudWatch metrics with alarms triggering Lambda for automated remediation", "C. Weekly reviews", "D. No detection"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CloudWatch alarms monitor metrics and trigger Lambda functions or SNS notifications to enable automated incident response."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "A company wants to implement GitOps where infrastructure changes are applied only from a Git repository. Which combination best achieves this?", "options": ["A. Manual CloudFormation deployments with Git for version control", "B. CodeCommit + CodePipeline + CloudFormation with protected main branch and pipeline-only deployment permissions", "C. Developers with direct console access using git for documentation", "D. CodeBuild running terraform plan on every commit with manual apply"], "answer": 1, "explain": "True GitOps uses Git as the source of truth. Protected branches prevent direct commits, and only the pipeline (not humans) has permissions to deploy, ensuring all changes go through Git."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "Your pipeline needs conditional deployment based on test results. How can this be implemented?", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "Which CloudWatch feature allows you to create an alarm that fires only when multiple underlying alarms are in ALARM state?", "options": ["A. CloudWatch Compound Alarms", "B. CloudWatch Composite Alarms", "C. CloudWatch Metric Math", "D. CloudWatch Dashboard alerts"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Composite Alarms combine multiple CloudWatch alarms using Boolean logic (AND/OR/NOT). They help reduce alert fatigue by only firing when a combination of conditions is met."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "A CloudFormation template creates resources in a specific order. A Lambda function needs to be invoked after all other resources are created. How do you implement this as part of the stack creation?", "options": ["A. Use CloudFormation Outputs to trigger Lambda", "B. Use a CloudFormation Custom Resource that triggers the Lambda function", "C. Use EventBridge to detect stack creation complete", "D. Add a DependsOn on every resource pointing to Lambda"], "answer": 1, "explain": "A Custom Resource backed by Lambda runs as part of stack lifecycle. Setting DependsOn on the Custom Resource from all other resources ensures Lambda is invoked only after all dependencies are created."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "A company needs to modify a CloudFormation stack parameter without causing resource replacement. What is the safest approach?", "options": ["A. Delete and recreate the stack", "B. Use UpdateStack operation; ensure UpdateReplacePolicy prevents critical resource replacement", "C. Manually modify resources", "D. Create a new stack"], "answer": 1, "explain": "UpdateStack allows modifying parameters without full stack deletion. UpdateReplacePolicy protects critical resources from replacement."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "Which CodeDeploy deployment configuration minimizes risk by deploying to one instance at a time and stopping if an error occurs?", "options": ["A. CodeDeployDefault.AllAtOnce", "B. CodeDeployDefault.HalfAtATime", "C. CodeDeployDefault.OneAtATime", "D. CodeDeployDefault.Linear10PercentEvery1Minute"], "answer": 2, "explain": "OneAtATime deploys to one instance at a time and stops the deployment if any failure occurs, providing maximum safety but slower deployment."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "A Lambda function needs a database connection string that changes periodically. How do you ensure the function always uses the current value without redeployment?", "options": ["A. Hardcode the connection string in the Lambda code", "B. Use AWS Secrets Manager with automatic rotation; Lambda retrieves the secret at runtime", "C. Store in environment variables and redeploy when changed", "D. Use DynamoDB to store the connection string"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Secrets Manager automatically rotates secrets and Lambda retrieves the current value at runtime via the Secrets Manager API. No redeployment is needed when the secret rotates."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "A CodePipeline pipeline needs to build artifacts using CodeBuild and then store them for future use. Where are CodePipeline artifacts stored by default?", "options": ["A. CodeCommit repository", "B. ECR registry", "C. S3 artifact bucket", "D. EFS mount"], "answer": 2, "explain": "CodePipeline uses an S3 bucket as the artifact store. All artifacts passed between pipeline stages are stored and retrieved from this S3 bucket, which is encrypted by default."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "A company uses AWS CDK for infrastructure. They want to add CDK deployments to CodePipeline. Which CDK construct provides a complete CI/CD pipeline?", "options": ["A. CDK Bootstrap", "B. CDK Pipelines (pipelines.CodePipeline construct)", "C. CDK Deploy action", "D. CDK Toolkit"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CDK Pipelines is a high-level construct that creates a self-mutating CodePipeline pipeline for CDK applications, handling synthesis, testing, and deployment across accounts and regions."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "Your infrastructure needs to automatically scale resources when monitoring detects high load. What services should be integrated?", "options": ["A. Manual scaling", "B. CloudWatch alarms triggering Auto Scaling policies or Lambda-based scaling", "C. Scheduled scaling", "D. No scaling"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CloudWatch alarms can trigger Auto Scaling policies to adjust capacity based on metrics, or invoke Lambda for custom scaling logic."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "What happens when a CodePipeline source stage detects a new commit while a pipeline execution is already in progress?", "options": ["A. The new commit is immediately queued and starts a new execution", "B. The new commit is queued and starts after the current execution completes (superseded mode) or can be configured to run in parallel", "C. The new commit is ignored until the pipeline is idle", "D. CodePipeline immediately cancels the current execution and starts a new one"], "answer": 1, "explain": "By default, CodePipeline queues the new revision and either supersedes the in-progress execution (Superseded mode) or allows parallel executions depending on pipeline settings."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "A security team needs to know immediately when an S3 bucket's public access block settings are disabled. Which service sends the fastest notification?", "options": ["A. AWS Config rule with notification on change", "B. CloudTrail + EventBridge rule matching the PutBucketPublicAccessBlock API call → SNS immediate notification", "C. Daily S3 Security Hub report", "D. S3 server access logging review"], "answer": 1, "explain": "EventBridge captures CloudTrail events in near-real-time. A rule matching PutBucketPublicAccessBlock calls that remove public access blocks triggers instant SNS notification, far faster than Config's evaluation cycle."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "A CI/CD pipeline deploys to production 20 times per day. The team wants to automatically rollback when error rate exceeds 5%. Which combination achieves this?", "options": ["A. Manual monitoring with on-call engineer", "B. CloudWatch alarm on error rate → EventBridge → Lambda triggers CodeDeploy rollback", "C. CodeDeploy automatic rollback based on CloudWatch alarm threshold", "D. CodePipeline manual approval gate for every deployment"], "answer": 2, "explain": "CodeDeploy supports automatic rollback when configured CloudWatch alarms breach thresholds. This provides immediate, automated rollback without human intervention, critical for high-frequency deployment pipelines."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "A pipeline deploys a CloudFormation stack. You need the pipeline to wait for the stack deployment to complete before proceeding. What action type handles this?", "options": ["A. CodeBuild action with CLI polling", "B. CloudFormation action type in CodePipeline (Deploy mode)", "C. Lambda action that polls CloudFormation", "D. Manual approval after CloudFormation action"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CodePipeline's CloudFormation action natively waits for stack operations to complete (CREATE_COMPLETE, UPDATE_COMPLETE) before marking the action as succeeded and proceeding to the next stage."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "A company wants to automatically create CloudWatch dashboards whenever a new application stack is deployed via CloudFormation. How do you implement this?", "options": ["A. Manually create dashboards after each deployment", "B. Include AWS::CloudWatch::Dashboard resource in the CloudFormation template", "C. Use CloudWatch automatic dashboards", "D. Use a Lambda function triggered after deployment"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CloudFormation can create and manage CloudWatch dashboards as stack resources. Including AWS::CloudWatch::Dashboard in the template automatically provisions dashboards with appropriate metrics when the stack is deployed."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "A team wants to implement automated testing within CodePipeline. Where should tests execute?", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "A team's CodeBuild build passes but the deployed application fails in production due to missing environment-specific configuration. Which pattern prevents this?", "options": ["A. Hardcode all environment configs in the build", "B. Use CodePipeline with separate deploy stages per environment; inject environment-specific config from Parameter Store during deployment", "C. Deploy identically to all environments", "D. Use different CodeBuild projects per environment"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Environment-specific configuration (endpoints, credentials) should be injected at deploy time from Parameter Store or Secrets Manager, not baked into the build. This ensures the same artifact deploys consistently across environments."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "Which Elastic Beanstalk deployment policy replaces all instances with new instances running the new application version, providing the highest stability?", "options": ["A. Rolling", "B. Immutable", "C. Rolling with additional batch", "D. All at once"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Immutable deployment launches a completely new set of instances with the new version. Only after the new instances pass health checks are old instances terminated, providing easy rollback and no in-place changes."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "A company enables AWS Config in all regions. They want a unified compliance dashboard. Which service aggregates Config data from multiple regions and accounts?", "options": ["A. CloudWatch cross-region dashboards", "B. AWS Config Aggregator", "C. AWS Security Hub", "D. AWS Organizations with Config"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Config Aggregators collect configuration and compliance data from multiple accounts and regions into a single view. They provide a centralized compliance dashboard without requiring manual correlation of regional Config data."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "A company needs to ensure their CloudFormation stacks are deployed identically across multiple regions for DR purposes. What is the most efficient approach?", "options": ["A. Manually deploy the same template in each region", "B. Use CloudFormation StackSets to deploy across multiple regions from a single operation", "C. Use CodePipeline with parallel regional deployment stages", "D. Copy templates to each region and deploy separately"], "answer": 1, "explain": "StackSets deploy identical stacks across multiple regions and accounts simultaneously, ensuring consistency. StackSets handle drift detection and can update all regional stacks in a single operation."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "CodePipeline integration with external systems requires custom logic. What mechanism enables this?", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "You need to compile Java source code, run unit and integration tests, and create a deployable artifact. What is the most appropriate AWS service?", "options": ["A. AWS Lambda for compilation", "B. AWS CodeBuild with buildspec.yml for controlled builds", "C. AWS EC2 with scripts", "D. AWS CodeDeploy"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CodeBuild provides a managed build environment where you define build steps in buildspec.yml, including compilation, testing, and artifact creation."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "Which feature of AWS CodeGuru Reviewer helps improve code quality in a CI/CD pipeline?", "options": ["A. Automatically deploys code to production", "B. Performs automated code reviews using ML to detect bugs and security vulnerabilities", "C. Monitors application performance in production", "D. Manages code merge conflicts in CodeCommit"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CodeGuru Reviewer uses machine learning to analyze code changes in pull requests and automatically provides recommendations for bugs, security issues, and deviation from AWS best practices."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "An organization wants to automatically quarantine an EC2 instance when GuardDuty detects a cryptocurrency mining finding. What is the most automated solution?", "options": ["A. Have the security team review GuardDuty findings daily", "B. EventBridge rule matches GuardDuty finding → Lambda isolates instance by modifying its security group", "C. Use AWS Inspector to scan the instance", "D. Terminate the instance immediately upon any GuardDuty finding"], "answer": 1, "explain": "EventBridge can match specific GuardDuty finding types and trigger Lambda. Lambda can isolate the instance by replacing its security groups with a quarantine SG that blocks all traffic while preserving the instance for forensics."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "Which CloudFormation intrinsic function retrieves the value of an attribute from another resource in the same stack?", "options": ["A. Ref", "B. Fn::GetAtt", "C. Fn::ImportValue", "D. Fn::Sub"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Fn::GetAtt returns specific attributes of resources (e.g., the endpoint URL of an RDS instance, the ARN of an IAM role). Ref typically returns just the resource's logical ID or primary identifier."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "Your organization has multiple incident response procedures for different scenarios.", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "A team uses Terraform but needs to manage some resources with CloudFormation. Which feature allows importing existing resources into a CloudFormation stack?", "options": ["A. CloudFormation Drift Detection", "B. CloudFormation Resource Import", "C. CloudFormation StackSets", "D. AWS Config resource import"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CloudFormation Resource Import allows you to bring existing AWS resources under CloudFormation management without recreating them, specifying a unique identifier for each resource."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "A company wants to automatically take snapshots of RDS instances before applying changes as a safety measure. Which approach automates this?", "options": ["A. Manually create snapshots before each change", "B. Use AWS Backup with a policy that creates RDS snapshots on a schedule and before CloudFormation updates", "C. Enable automated backups in RDS only", "D. Use Lambda to trigger RDS snapshots based on CloudTrail events"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS Backup provides centralized, policy-driven backup management. Pre-change snapshots can be automated using Backup plans or Lambda functions triggered by EventBridge when CloudFormation stack updates are initiated."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "A company uses a NAT Gateway for outbound internet access. If the AZ containing the NAT Gateway fails, instances in other AZs lose internet access. How do you fix this?", "options": ["A. Increase NAT Gateway bandwidth", "B. Create a NAT Gateway in each AZ and update route tables for each AZ's subnet to use its local NAT Gateway", "C. Use a NAT instance for better reliability", "D. Use VPC endpoints for all internet access"], "answer": 1, "explain": "NAT Gateways are single-AZ. Deploy one in each AZ and configure each AZ's private subnet route table to use its local NAT Gateway. This eliminates cross-AZ NAT Gateway dependency."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "An Auto Scaling group needs to add instances only when CPU exceeds 70% for at least 10 minutes, not on brief spikes. How do you configure this?", "options": ["A. Set the scaling policy threshold to 70%", "B. Set the scaling policy with a CloudWatch alarm that uses an evaluation period of 2 data points over 10-minute periods", "C. Use scheduled scaling at known peak times", "D. Use predictive scaling"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CloudWatch alarms can require multiple consecutive breach periods (evaluation periods x period duration) before firing. Setting 2 periods x 5 minutes = 10 minutes prevents scaling on brief spikes."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "A company needs artifact version control for their builds. How does CodeArtifact help with this?", "options": ["A. It replaces CodeCommit for source code versioning", "B. It provides immutable versioned package storage with upstream proxying and npm/Maven/PyPI compatibility", "C. It automatically versions EC2 AMIs", "D. It versions Lambda function code"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CodeArtifact stores immutable package versions with full provenance. Packages can't be overwritten, ensuring build reproducibility. It proxies public registries and caches packages for availability and security."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "Your infrastructure requires different configurations for dev, staging, and production.", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "A company wants to identify AWS resources that are not compliant with their tagging policy across all regions. Which service provides this visibility?", "options": ["A. CloudTrail log analysis", "B. AWS Config with a required-tags Config rule across all regions", "C. Custom Lambda function scanning all resources", "D. AWS Cost Explorer tag coverage report"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS Config's required-tags managed rule checks that specified tags exist on resources. Deploying this rule across all regions and accounts via StackSets provides comprehensive tag compliance monitoring."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "An Auto Scaling group uses a launch template. You update the template with a new AMI. How do instance updates roll out?", "options": ["A. All existing instances are immediately replaced", "B. Existing instances keep the old AMI; new instances use the new AMI. Use instance refresh to replace existing instances.", "C. Auto Scaling automatically replaces instances over 24 hours", "D. The launch template update triggers a rolling replacement automatically"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Launch template updates don't automatically replace running instances. Use Auto Scaling Instance Refresh to perform a controlled rolling replacement, replacing instances in batches with configurable minimum healthy percentage."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "An application's RDS database is experiencing high read latency during peak hours. Without changing the application code, what is the fastest mitigation?", "options": ["A. Upgrade RDS instance size", "B. Create an RDS Read Replica and point read traffic to it", "C. Enable Multi-AZ for RDS", "D. Enable RDS Performance Insights"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Read Replicas offload read traffic from the primary instance. For immediate mitigation, adding a read replica and updating the connection string (or using Route 53 DNS) redirects reads without code changes."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "A team needs to identify the top 10 IP addresses making the most requests to their application load balancer over the last hour. Which service provides this analysis most efficiently?", "options": ["A. Query ALB access logs in S3 using Amazon Athena", "B. Enable CloudWatch detailed monitoring on the ALB", "C. Use VPC Flow Logs with CloudWatch Logs Insights", "D. Review the ALB console metrics"], "answer": 0, "explain": "ALB access logs stored in S3 can be queried with Athena using SQL, enabling efficient analysis of large log volumes including top talkers, error patterns, and latency analysis."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "Your organization wants a graceful degradation approach where services remain available.", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "Your container application needs to monitor logs from hundreds of ECS containers.", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "A critical production database has connectivity issues. What is the recommended approach to diagnose and resolve quickly?", "options": ["A. Manual investigation", "B. Systems Manager Session Manager for direct access, combined with troubleshooting automation", "C. Restart everything", "D. Manual logs"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Systems Manager Session Manager provides secure shell access without SSH keys; combined with Systems Manager Automation, this enables rapid diagnosis."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "A company wants to automatically trigger CodePipeline execution whenever code is pushed to CodeCommit. What is the recommended approach?", "options": ["A. Manual triggering via AWS Console", "B. EventBridge rule detecting CodeCommit push events", "C. Scheduled execution every 5 minutes", "D. CodeCommit polling every minute"], "answer": 1, "explain": "EventBridge rules can automatically detect CodeCommit push events and trigger CodePipeline execution in real-time without polling overhead."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "CodeDeploy needs to know how to deploy your application to EC2 instances. Which file defines deployment actions, lifecycle event hooks, and deployment configuration?", "options": ["A. buildspec.yml", "B. appspec.yml or appspec.json", "C. cloudformation.yml", "D. deployment.json"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The AppSpec file defines deployment actions, lifecycle events (BeforeInstall, AfterInstall, ApplicationStart), and CodeDeploy deployment behavior."}, {"cat": "config-incident", "q": "Which Systems Manager feature allows you to track and apply OS and application patches to a fleet of instances on a schedule?", "options": ["A. Run Command", "B. Patch Manager with Maintenance Windows", "C. State Manager", "D. Inventory"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Patch Manager defines patch baselines (approved patches) and Maintenance Windows schedule when patching occurs. Together they automate patch compliance across your fleet."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "A microservice has multiple upstream dependencies. When dependency A is slow, requests queue up and exhaust the thread pool, causing failures for all services. Which pattern prevents this?", "options": ["A. Increase thread pool size", "B. Implement the Circuit Breaker pattern", "C. Add more service instances", "D. Use synchronous retries with exponential backoff"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The Circuit Breaker pattern detects when a dependency is failing and 'opens' the circuit, returning errors immediately instead of queuing requests. This prevents cascading failures and allows the system to operate in degraded mode."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "Your organization wants to automatically respond to security events detected by GuardDuty. What integration enables this?", "options": ["A. Manual response only", "B. EventBridge rules routing GuardDuty findings to Lambda or Systems Manager Automation", "C. CloudWatch alarms only", "D. Manual scripts"], "answer": 1, "explain": "EventBridge can route GuardDuty findings to automation systems for automated security incident response."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "A team needs to verify their CloudFormation deployments are not causing configuration drift from their baseline. Which combination provides continuous monitoring?", "options": ["A. Manual CloudFormation drift detection runs", "B. AWS Config rules that evaluate resources against desired configuration, triggered by configuration changes", "C. CloudWatch Events on CloudFormation stack updates", "D. Custom Lambda functions polling resource configurations"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS Config continuously records configuration changes and evaluates resources against Config rules. Change-triggered rules immediately evaluate modified resources, providing near-real-time compliance monitoring."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "A web application's static assets are served from S3 via CloudFront. During a deployment, new assets have the same file names. How do you ensure users get new content immediately?", "options": ["A. Set CloudFront TTL to 0", "B. Use versioned file names (e.g., app.v2.js) or create a CloudFront invalidation for changed files", "C. Disable CloudFront caching", "D. Use S3 Transfer Acceleration"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Versioned file names eliminate the need for invalidations and allow long cache TTLs (better performance). CloudFront invalidations are the alternative for non-versioned assets, but cost more and have propagation delays."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "A company wants to test their disaster recovery plan without causing production impact. Which approach validates DR capability?", "options": ["A. Only test DR during actual disasters", "B. Conduct regular DR drills using AWS Fault Injection Simulator (FIS) or by failing over to DR environment", "C. Review DR documentation quarterly", "D. Rely on AWS SLAs for high availability"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Regular DR drills (game days) validate that recovery procedures work as expected. AWS FIS enables controlled fault injection (AZ failure, instance termination) to test resilience without manual intervention."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "Your organization needs to serve requests from multiple regions with automatic failover if a region becomes unavailable. How should this be architected?", "options": ["A. Single region only", "B. Active-active regions with Route 53 failover and health checks", "C. Passive standby region", "D. Manual failover"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Active-active multi-region with Route 53 health checks enables automatic failover, maintaining availability if regions fail."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "A company uses GitHub Enterprise and wants native GitHub integration with CodePipeline without managing OAuth tokens. What should they use?", "options": ["A. GitHub personal access tokens stored in CodePipeline", "B. AWS CodeStar Connections for GitHub Enterprise", "C. CodeCommit mirroring from GitHub", "D. GitHub webhooks with API Gateway"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CodeStar Connections provides a managed, secure connection to GitHub, GitHub Enterprise, and Bitbucket. It uses OAuth app connections managed by AWS, eliminating the need to manage personal access tokens."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "Your AWS CDK application needs conditional resource creation based on environment.", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "Your incident response process requires multiple teams to be notified and coordinated.", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "monitoring-logging", "q": "Multi-region Load Balancer distribution should account for regional capacity differences.", "options": ["A. Manual approach", "B. Automated approach using AWS services", "C. No approach needed", "D. Accept the limitation"], "answer": 1, "explain": "AWS services provide automated solutions for DevOps challenges."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "A CodePipeline pipeline uses a manual approval action. The team needs to automatically notify approvers via email when approval is required. What is the recommended approach?", "options": ["A. Use a Lambda function to poll pipeline state", "B. Configure the approval action with an SNS topic ARN", "C. Set up CloudWatch Events on pipeline state", "D. Use SES directly in CodePipeline"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CodePipeline's manual approval action natively integrates with SNS. Specify an SNS topic and subscribers receive email notifications when approval is needed."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "An Elastic Beanstalk application needs custom software installed on instances before the application starts. What is the recommended approach?", "options": ["A. Use a custom AMI with pre-installed software", "B. Use .ebextensions configuration files to run commands during instance provisioning", "C. SSH to each instance and install software manually", "D. Use EC2 User Data scripts"], "answer": 1, "explain": ".ebextensions are YAML/JSON configuration files included in the application bundle. They run during instance provisioning and can install packages, create files, run commands, and configure AWS resources."}, {"cat": "sdlc-automation", "q": "In a CodePipeline, artifacts from the CodeBuild stage need to be passed to the CodeDeploy stage. Where should these artifacts be stored?", "options": ["A. EC2 instances", "B. Amazon S3 bucket designated as artifact store", "C. CodeCommit repository", "D. Local CodeBuild cache"], "answer": 1, "explain": "CodePipeline stores build artifacts in S3, allowing each stage to retrieve and use outputs from previous stages for deployment."}, {"cat": "high-availability", "q": "Your application requires zero-downtime deployments across multiple regions. What strategy enables this?", "options": ["A. Deploy to one region, then others sequentially", "B. Blue/green deployments with Route 53 traffic shifting across regions", "C. Single deployment", "D. Accept downtime"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Blue/green deployments across regions with Route 53 traffic management enable zero-downtime updates across all regions."}, {"cat": "incident-event-response", "q": "A company's application uses DynamoDB. During a traffic spike, they're hitting ProvisionedThroughputExceededException errors. What is the immediate mitigation?", "options": ["A. Switch to DynamoDB On-Demand capacity mode", "B. Increase provisioned read/write capacity units", "C. Enable DynamoDB Auto Scaling", "D. All of the above can help; On-Demand is immediate with no pre-configuration"], "answer": 3, "explain": "On-Demand capacity is the fastest mitigation (no scaling delays). Auto Scaling adjusts capacity based on usage but has scaling delays. Increasing provisioned capacity is immediate but requires knowing the target RCU/WCU."}];